Comment: Hello guys! Just finished reading the book and it made me cried! I definetly can’t wait to watch the movie versionI I can actually relate to the story, to Auggie. I was born with Anhidrotic Ectordermal Dysplasia. I was born with sharp teeth, small nose, thick lips, and no hairs. That made different from normal kids. And it was hard. My childhood-puberty was freaking awful. People are so mean. But thanks to my wonderful family and friends for making me feel that I’m not different. I earned my Bachelor Degree in Psychology last year. My graduation post became viral online here in the Philippines and I was so happy to inspire alot of people. And recently passed my licesure examination here in our country. Just keep on breaking the walls. As Olivia Pullman said, you can’t blend in when your born to stand out.

Title: Wonder (2017 Movie) Official Trailer – #ChooseKind – Julia Roberts, Owen Wilson
Comment: When my daughter ran in my room screaming about seeing this trailer today (it's our favorite book) I got so excited; until I saw the trailer. Now I just feel completely let down and disappointed. First of all, the actor who plays Aggie hardly looks like he has a facial-cranial deformity- so, basically, terrible make-up job, does not drive the point home about how severe Aggie's deformities are in the book. But, the fact that it is a make-up job just sends a terrible message to children with these deformities. A child with Treacher-Collins syndrome should have been cast as Aggie; to children with facial deformities this just sends the message that they are still not good enough- that their deformities are still too severe for them to be cast in a movie and that even a mask has to be watered down to be good enough for the public to sympathize. This is just shameful.

Title: Wonder (2017 Movie) Official Trailer – #ChooseKind – Julia Roberts, Owen Wilson
Comment: I am so excited for this movie!!! I had this book read aloud to me in 4th grade (I'm going into 9th now) and I fell in love with it. I have since read the book over 10 times, read all three side character stories, read 1 quote from 365 Days of Wonder every day for a year, and even met the author. I have done countless projects on this book. Every teacher I have tells me that this is too easy as I am reading on a 12th grade reading level which is true, but I love it so much that I read it in my free time. It sends a great message, and I wish it was a middle school requirement across the country. When this movie comes out fellow Wonder fans and I will be in the theaters watching! I hope teachers continue to read and inspire other teachers to read this to students because as a student who once had it read aloud, I can tell you first hand that it does make a difference! Remember, "When given the choice between being right and being kind, chose kind." The fact that I remember that quote and think about it on a daily basis nearly 5 years after the first time I hear Wonder shows I am just one kid among many more that this book has inspired!

Comment: Kids like this that struggle with something such as this tend to be some of the absolute best spirits and souls that you could ever encounter. Comment: Holly shit I could literally see a young version of myself sitting at the lunch table all alone as the main character did. My heart literally jumped at this. I have a studder and a heart condition so I always sort of stood out. Normally the heart condition wouldn't be a problem but there was this stupid board at school with kids who had possible life threatening conditions and kids would avoid me because they thought they could catch it. The fact I was taller then every kid when I was younger really didn't help that much also. Long story short this is so a movie I will be seeing. I will probably see it multiple times and then buy it after it comes out. Thank you whoever made this and everyone who had a part in making this. Feels like one for the underdogs and it feels great to get some awareness for bullying/growing up different:)
